      <div xml:id="NA233-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaiyātu neṭuṅ kālam vantoḻuka ivaḷ āṟṟāḷ eṉpatu uṇarntu ciṟaippuṟamākat talaimakaṭkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said when [HE] was behind the fences, having realised that she would not be able to bear it when [he] was coming for a long time without marrying.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA233">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kallāk kaṭuva ṉaṭuṅkamuḷ ḷeyiṟṟu</l>
<l>            maṭamā manti māṇā vaṉpaṟaḻ</l>
<l>            kōṭuya raṭukkat tāṭumaḻai yoḷikkum</l>
<l>            peruṅka ṉāṭaṉai yaruḷiṉai yāyi</l>
<l>            ṉiṉiyeṉa koḷḷalai maṉṉē koṉṉoṉṟu </l>
<l>            kūṟuvaṉ vāḻi tōḻi muṉṉuṟa</l>
<l>            nāruṭai neñcat tīram potti</l>
<l>            yāṉṟōr ceṉṉeṟi vāḻāc</l>
<l>            cāṉṟō ṉātaṉaṟ kaṟintaṉai terimē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">If you have consideration for the man from the land of big stones,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the rain<note place="foot">Or: "the clouds".</note> playing on the side high to the peak conceal</l>
<l rend="indent3">the thorn-toothed youthful dark she-monkey [and its]</l>
<l rend="indent3">unglorious(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">māṇā</term>: what is this supposed to mean in connection with the young of a monkey? T.V.G. explains it as a monkey too young yet to have learned to climb by itself, that is, still carried by the mother, but that looks rather scholastic without further references.</note> strong young one,</l>
<l rend="indent4">so that the uninformed male monkey shivers,</l>
<l>you do indeed not take it in right<note place="foot">Here the <term xml:lang="ta">eṉa</term> is a problem. T.V.G. wants to read it as a direct object of <term xml:lang="ta">koḷḷalai</term>, that is, as a participial noun n.pl. of eṉ, meaning words ("you don’t take in [my] words"), but should that not be either <term xml:lang="ta">eṉṟa</term> or <term xml:lang="ta">eṉpa</term>, some kind of aspectual infix? I suggest to take it as a kind of weakened adverbial formans used here for emphasis (cf. <term xml:lang="ta">taṇṇeṉa</term>).</note> now.</l>
<l rend="indent4">One thing</l>
<l>I will tell [you], oh friend.</l>
<l>You have well realised that he is a noble one</l>
<l rend="indent">who does not live according to the path followed by noble men,</l>
<l rend="indent2">having buried the pliability of [his] previously loving<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nār-uṭai neñcattu</term>: here the opposite to the formulaic <term xml:lang="ta">nāril neñcam</term>. In the negative the translation works quite will with "bond", the literal meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">nār</term>, but the positive version has to be circumscribed and thereby, as so often, diluted.</note> heart.</l>
<l rend="indent3">Understand [this].</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
